We cannot then be far wrong in preferring the consistent and probable account of Polybius to the vague and contradictory state- ments of Livy. Two points remain to be considered; the question of the details of Hannibal's march, and the further question of how, supposing it to be erroneous, the account followed by Livy arose.

On the first of these questions, the details given by Coelius are clearly wrong. For Hannibal to have gone from Sulmo to the Marrucini would have served excellently to mystify curiosity as to his objective‚ but could hardly have served any other purpose.
